	<h2>Understanding Security Needs in Stockton</h2>
	<p>Stockton's property crime statistics make security a legitimate concern for homeowners. However, effective security fencing isn't about building walls—it's about implementing strategic barriers that deter criminals while maintaining neighborhood aesthetics and complying with local regulations.</p>

	<p>Criminal psychology studies consistently show that visible security measures significantly reduce property crime risk. Burglars typically spend less than 60 seconds assessing a target; a well-designed security fence creates perceived effort and risk that encourages them to move on to easier targets. The key is implementing security features that work psychologically without creating an oppressive visual environment.</p>

	<h3>Key Security Principles for Stockton Homes</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Access Control:</strong> Limit entry points and make unauthorized access difficult</li>
		<li><strong>Visibility:</strong> Balance privacy with ability to see approaching threats</li>
		<li><strong>Surveillance Integration:</strong> Design fencing to accommodate cameras and lighting</li>
		<li><strong>Delay and Deter:</strong> Slow down intruders and make your property less appealing</li>
		<li><strong>Community Context:</strong> Match neighborhood security levels to avoid standing out</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Security Fence Materials: Comparing Options for Stockton Homes</h2>

	<h3>Ornamental Iron and Aluminum Fencing</h3>
	<p><strong>Why It Works for Security:</strong> Ornamental metal fencing provides exceptional security while maintaining an upscale, welcoming appearance. Unlike chain link, quality ornamental fencing enhances property values while deterring intruders.</p>

	<p><strong>Security Features:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Height:</strong> 6-8 feet tall creates significant barrier (Stockton allows 6' in rear yards, check regulations for taller installations)</li>
		<li><strong>Picket Spacing:</strong> 4-inch spacing prevents body passage while maintaining visibility</li>
		<li><strong>Finial Tips:</strong> Decorative spear points or rings discourage climbing</li>
		<li><strong>Welded Construction:</strong> Panels can't be easily disassembled like chain link</li>
		<li><strong>Gate Security:</strong> Integrated locking systems with heavy-duty latches</li>
		<li><strong>Anti-Climb Design:</strong> No horizontal rails or footholds for climbing</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Performance in Stockton Climate:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Aluminum:</strong> Never rusts, ideal for Stockton's occasional rain and morning Delta moisture. Lightweight but strong. Powder coating lasts 20+ years without fading in Central Valley sun.</li>
		<li><strong>Steel:</strong> Stronger and more rigid than aluminum, better for high-security applications. Requires quality powder coating or galvanizing to prevent rust in humid Delta air.</li>
		<li><strong>Heat Performance:</strong> Both materials withstand Stockton's 100°F+ summers without warping or degradation</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Cost Analysis:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Aluminum Ornamental:</strong> $25-45 per linear foot installed (4-6 foot height)</li>
		<li><strong>Steel Ornamental:</strong> $30-60 per linear foot installed (stronger, heavier gauge)</li>
		<li><strong>Commercial-Grade:</strong> $45-80 per linear foot for enhanced security applications</li>
		<li><strong>Typical 150 LF Backyard:</strong> $3,750-9,000 depending on height and material</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Design Options for Stockton Homes:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Traditional Estate:</strong> Decorative scrollwork and finials complement Victorian and Craftsman homes</li>
