		<li>Aluminum-reinforced posts and rails add strength</li>
		<li>Quality locking gates essential (vinyl alone not as secure as metal frames)</li>
		<li>UV-stabilized formulations prevent brittleness in Stockton's intense sun</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Advanced Security Features and Upgrades</h2>

	<h3>Gates: Your Security Weak Point</h3>
	<p>Gates represent the most vulnerable point in any security fence system. Investing in high-quality gates and locking mechanisms is essential for effective security.</p>

	<p><strong>Gate Security Enhancements:</strong></p>

	<p><strong>Lock Systems:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Basic Gravity Latches:</strong> Minimal security, suitable only for privacy not security</li>
		<li><strong>Keyed Gate Locks:</strong> $50-150, standard security for pedestrian gates</li>
		<li><strong>Deadbolts:</strong> $75-200, commercial-grade security for residential gates</li>
		<li><strong>Electronic Locks:</strong> $150-500, keypad or smartphone control, access logs</li>
		<li><strong>Smart Locks:</strong> $200-600, integration with home security systems, remote access</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Automatic Gate Systems:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Swing Gate Operators:</strong> $1,200-3,000 installed, ideal for driveways</li>
		<li><strong>Slide Gate Operators:</strong> $1,500-4,000 installed, better for sloped driveways</li>
		<li><strong>Access Control:</strong> Remote controls, keypads, smartphone apps, vehicle sensors</li>
		<li><strong>Safety Features:</strong> Auto-reverse, obstruction sensors (required by California law)</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Gate Construction for Maximum Security:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Heavy-duty hinges (minimum 3 for 6-foot tall gates)</li>
		<li>Steel frame construction, even with wood or vinyl infill</li>
		<li>Cane bolt bottom drop rods prevent lifting from bottom</li>
		<li>Anti-lift brackets prevent gate being lifted off hinges</li>
		<li>Reinforced corners with welded or through-bolted connections</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Anti-Climb Features</h3>
	<p><strong>Design Elements That Prevent Climbing:</strong></p>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>Fence Top Treatments:</strong>
			<ul>
				<li>Rotating or pointed finials on ornamental fencing</li>
				<li>Angled lattice extensions on wood fences (add 1-2 feet height)</li>
				<li>Rolled top edges (commercial application, may look institutional)</li>
				<li>Decorative "Gothic" points that are functional and attractive</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
		<li><strong>Eliminate Horizontal Rails:</strong> Install on interior side only, or use styles without horizontal members</li>
		<li><strong>Smooth Surfaces:</strong> Avoid textures or projections that provide handholds</li>
		<li><strong>Height Advantage:</strong> 6-foot minimum, 8-foot where code allows (may require variance)</li>
		<li><strong>Barrier Additions:</strong>
			<ul>
				<li>Thick, thorny plants (bougainvillea, roses, pyracantha) at fence base</li>
				<li>Gravel beds create noise when stepped on</li>
				<li>Motion-activated lighting at fence line</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
	</ul>

